name: Robin Monks
tweet: In late-night summary: 5G is only good if it makes companies fix their infrastructure, and then LTE will get better too. Don’t let your telco convince you to pay more for their over-hyped new toy.

name: Robin Monks
tweet: Some of the misleading statements I’ve seen: - 5G will allow real-time navigation (even 3G can do that) - 5G will power hospital surgeries (no, hospitals use fibre internet) - 5G will allow super-fast rural internet for homes (no, the signal doesn’t carry well enough for that)

name: Robin Monks
tweet: 5G mmwave basically requires hyper dense small tower deployments, and even then it will struggle to pass through walls into buildings. The technology just… doesn’t make sense in practice. 5G is a lot of hype, and a lot of misleading marketing.

name: Robin Monks
tweet: Current LTE is fast enough to stream 4K video to your phone. It can handle two-way HD video chat, it supports IPv6 for better device identification. It’s also low-latency. 5G is a bit of an odd-duck. It’s fastest with millimetre wave transmission but that can’t travel far.

name: Robin Monks
tweet: The issue with current LTE implementations isn’t the technology, it’s shoddy network management, throttling and congestion. All of that won’t be fixed by changing the transmitters to 5G. It’s caused by companies not investing in their networks and trying to extract max profit.

name: Robin Monks
tweet: 5G is not going to make a difference in your life. All the marketing and campaigns around 5G are horrible hype. Nothing you do on your phone is going to be different with 5G, and don’t let companies try and convince you otherwise.
